(43, 5, 6, 43, 21, 17, 17, 'Wilt thou be made whole?', 'Healing and Restoration Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of restoration in both passages. In John 5:6, Jesus asks if the man wants to be made whole, while in John 21:17, He restores Peter by asking if he loves Him, emphasizing care and nurturing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 6, 19, 142, 3, 3, 'Wilt thou be made whole?', 'Connection of Overwhelmed Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize a state of distress and the need for healing or guidance. In John 5:6, the question of being made whole reflects a desire for restoration, while Psalms 142:3 speaks to an overwhelmed spirit seeking a path amidst challenges.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 6, 24, 13, 27, 27, 'wilt thou be made whole?', 'Healing and Cleansing Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of restoration and the desire for wholeness. Both passages pose a question about the willingness to be made whole or clean, emphasizing a call for transformation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 7, 19, 72, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Need and Help', 'Both passages emphasize the plight of those in need, highlighting the absence of support. The impotent man in John expresses his lack of a helper, paralleling the theme of deliverance for the needy in Psalms.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 7, 5, 32, 36, 36, NULL, 'Connection of Human Helplessness', 'Both passages emphasize a state of powerlessness. In John 5:7, the impotent man expresses his inability to reach the healing waters, while Deuteronomy 32:36 speaks of the Lord''s recognition of His people''s lost power.', 'theme', 0.37, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 7, 46, 9, 24, 24, 'no man, when the water is troubled', 'Race and Struggle for Healing', 'This connection highlights the struggle of the impotent man who seeks healing but faces obstacles, paralleling the race metaphor in Corinthians where runners strive to obtain a prize. Both passages emphasize the effort required to achieve one''s goals amidst challenges.', 'theme', 0.356, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 7, 19, 142, 4, 4, NULL, 'Isolation and Lack of Support', 'This connection highlights the theme of isolation and the absence of support in both passages. The impotent man feels abandoned as he lacks someone to help him, paralleling the psalmist''s experience of having no one who cares for his soul.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 7, 47, 1, 8, 10, NULL, 'Despair and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize a sense of despair and the need for divine intervention. The impotent man''s helplessness parallels the despair expressed by Paul, highlighting reliance on God for deliverance.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 7, 45, 5, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Human Weakness', 'This connection highlights the theme of human inability and the need for divine intervention. Both passages emphasize being ''without strength'' and the necessity of help from Christ for those who cannot help themselves.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 7, 43, 5, 3, 3, 'impotent man', 'Connection of Impotent Folk', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of ''impotent'' individuals waiting for healing. The first verse illustrates the man''s struggle to reach the pool, while the second sets the scene of many such individuals gathered in anticipation.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 8, 42, 5, 24, 24, 'take up thy bed, and walk', 'Healing and Authority of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' command to rise and walk, showcasing His authority over physical ailments. The similar phrasing highlights the miraculous healing performed by Jesus, reinforcing His power to heal and forgive sins.', 'parallel', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 8, 40, 9, 6, 6, 'take up thy bed', 'Healing and Authority of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' command to the sick to ''take up thy bed,'' showcasing His authority to heal and forgive sins. This connection highlights the miraculous power of Jesus in restoring health and the significance of His words.', 'parallel', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 8, 41, 2, 11, 11, 'take up thy bed', 'Healing Commands in Gospels', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus commanding a healing action. The phrases ''take up thy bed'' and ''arise'' are central to both healings, showcasing a similar miracle performed by Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 8, 44, 9, 34, 34, NULL, 'Healing and Command to Arise', 'Both passages emphasize a command to arise and walk, highlighting the theme of healing through Jesus'' authority. The phrase ''arise'' connects the miraculous acts performed by Jesus and Peter.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 9, 43, 9, 14, 14, 'on the same day was the sabbath', 'Sabbath Healing Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize miraculous healings performed by Jesus on the sabbath. This connection highlights the significance of these acts occurring on a day traditionally associated with rest.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 9, 44, 3, 7, 8, 'and walked', 'Healing and Walking on the Sabbath', 'Both passages emphasize immediate healing and the act of walking. In John 5:9, the healed man walks on the Sabbath, while in Acts 3:7-8, the healed man also stands and walks, praising God. This connection highlights the theme of miraculous healing leading to physical movement.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 9, 41, 3, 2, 4, 'on the same day was the sabbath', 'Sabbath Healing Controversy', 'Both passages emphasize healing on the Sabbath, highlighting the tension between doing good and adhering to the law. The question of legality regarding actions on the Sabbath is central to both narratives.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 9, 40, 12, 10, 13, 'on the same day was the sabbath', 'Sabbath Healing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize healing on the Sabbath, highlighting the tension between religious law and acts of compassion. The healing of the man with the withered hand in Matthew parallels the healing of the man who took up his bed in John, illustrating the theme of doing good on the Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 9, 41, 1, 31, 31, 'immediately', 'Healing and Immediate Response', 'Both passages emphasize immediate healing and restoration. In John 5:9, the man is made whole and walks, while in Mark 1:31, the fever leaves the woman immediately, showcasing a theme of swift divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 9, 42, 13, 10, 16, NULL, 'Healing on the Sabbath', 'Both passages emphasize healing performed by Jesus on the Sabbath, showcasing the conflict between divine compassion and religious law. The immediate healing in John parallels the healing of the woman in Luke, highlighting Jesus'' authority over Sabbath restrictions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 9, 43, 5, 10, 12, 'on the same day was the sabbath', 'Sabbath Healing Controversy', 'This connection highlights the conflict over the Sabbath law. Both passages emphasize the act of carrying the bed, which was deemed unlawful on the Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 10, 24, 17, 21, 21, NULL, 'Sabbath Burden Regulations', 'Both passages emphasize the prohibition of bearing burdens on the Sabbath. John 5:10 reflects the application of this law in a healing context, while Jeremiah 17:21 establishes the original commandment regarding Sabbath observance.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 10, 42, 6, 2, 2, 'not lawful for thee to carry thy bed', 'Sabbath Law Violation', 'Both passages emphasize actions deemed unlawful on the Sabbath. The Jews in John question the healing and carrying of the bed, while the Pharisees in Luke challenge actions taken on the Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 10, 43, 9, 16, 16, 'it is not lawful for thee to carry thy bed', 'Sabbath Controversy Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict surrounding the Sabbath. In John 5:10, the healed man is confronted for carrying his bed on the Sabbath, while in John 9:16, the Pharisees debate Jesus'' actions on the Sabbath, leading to division among them.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 10, 41, 3, 4, 4, 'it is not lawful for thee', 'Sabbath Law and Good Deeds', 'This connection highlights the tension between Sabbath law and doing good. Both passages emphasize the question of what is lawful on the Sabbath, particularly in relation to healing and helping others.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 10, 42, 13, 14, 14, 'it is not lawful for thee to carry thy bed', 'Sabbath Healing Controversy', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict surrounding healing on the sabbath. They highlight the indignation of religious leaders regarding actions taken on this day, specifically the prohibition against work.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 10, 16, 13, 15, 21, 'it is not lawful for thee to carry thy bed', 'Sabbath Observance and Law', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of sabbath observance and the consequences of violating it. In John 5:10, the healed man is confronted for carrying his bed on the sabbath, while Nehemiah 13:15-21 condemns various activities that profane the sabbath.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 10, 41, 2, 24, 24, 'not lawful for thee to carry thy bed', 'Sabbath Law Observance', 'Both passages emphasize the issue of what is lawful on the Sabbath. They highlight the conflict between healing and the strict interpretation of Sabbath laws.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 11, 41, 2, 9, 11, 'Take up thy bed, and walk', 'Healing and Authority Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the command to ''take up thy bed, and walk,'' highlighting the authority of Jesus to heal and forgive sins. This connection illustrates the relationship between physical healing and spiritual restoration.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 5, 11, 43, 9, 16, 16, 'Take up thy bed, and walk', 'Sabbath Controversy and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing on the Sabbath, which leads to division among the Pharisees. The healed man in John 5 refers to the command to ''take up thy bed,'' while John 9 discusses the implications of performing miracles on the Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
